<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/27606377-sandy-millin"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1630343493i/27606377._UX100_CR0,25,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/27606377-sandy-millin">Sandy Millin</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">In old books, several pages were printed on a single sheet of paper and the reader would have to cut (separate) the pages themselves. You can read mor<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">In old books, several pages were printed on a single sheet of paper and the reader would have to cut (separate) the pages themselves. You can read more in number 5 here: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://wwword.com/1585/words/jargon/rare-book-dealer/">http://wwword.com/1585/words/jargon/r...</a> A page cutter is a special tool for this, but I think a paper knife was used a lot from what I've just read. I can't seem to find a picture of a page cutter.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
