    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_171543599" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/171543599" />
    <a title="Sara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5512657-sara"><img alt="Sara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1543780395p2/5512657.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/171543599?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sara" href="/user/show/5512657-sara">Sara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9781501968525" href="/book/show/38135574-84-charing-cross-road">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5512657-sara?shelf=epistolary">epistolary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5512657-sara?shelf=audio">audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5512657-sara?shelf=women-writers">women-writers</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer171543599" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12193705071715365655"><i>Why is it that people who wouldn’t dream of stealing anything else think it&apos;s perfectly alright to steal books?</i><br/><br/>Now there is a question I would like to have answered. It comes from the correspondence of Helene Hanff, and it speaks to her love of books and her cheeky relationship with the man in receipt of her letters.<br/><br/>The lovely correspondence of Helene Hanff, a New York bibliophile, and Frank Doel, a British bookseller, with occasional letters from others thrown in to round out the story, takes p</span>
  <span id="freeText12193705071715365655" style="display:none"><i>Why is it that people who wouldn’t dream of stealing anything else think it's perfectly alright to steal books?</i><br /><br />Now there is a question I would like to have answered. It comes from the correspondence of Helene Hanff, and it speaks to her love of books and her cheeky relationship with the man in receipt of her letters.<br /><br />The lovely correspondence of Helene Hanff, a New York bibliophile, and Frank Doel, a British bookseller, with occasional letters from others thrown in to round out the story, takes place over a period from 1949 to 1969. You might think a correspondence in which the major part is the ordering and discussion of books would be boring, but it is anything but. Hanff has a healthy sense of humor and develops a true long-distance friendship with Doel; one that delights and causes the reader to smile. <br /><br />There is a certain feeling of camaraderie in this novel that is good for the soul. It made me feel as if everyone out in the wide world were part of a fellowship, and all that was needed was to stretch out your hand and another would take it and hold it in a friendly handshake of recognition.<br /><br />I read the book many years ago and remembered it as very sweet and touching. I believe I may have seen the movie with Anne Bancroft and Anthony Hopkins, as well, although I confess to not remembering it at all. This time I listened to the audio book (something I never, ever do) and found it was perhaps the perfect way to approach this material. Everything is there, nothing is cut or reinterpreted, and yet the voices add that human element that this book is so meant to convey.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12193705071715365655" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


